a shepherd. In Northamptonshire the name attracts excrescent <i>-s</i> already by 1377."],"variants":[{"name":"Beller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a bell founder or bell ringer, from Middle English <i>beller</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’. Compare   Bell   2.","German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called Bell in North Rhine-Westphalia or Bellen near Bremen.","German: nickname for a quarreller, from Middle High German <i>bellen</i> ‘to bicker, quarrel’."]},{"name":"Bellairs","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Bellars  , suggesting French <i>belle(s) aire(s)</i> ‘lovely demeanor’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Bellais was born in 1150, in England, his father, Robert de Bellais, was 20 and his mother, Beatrix Southwell de Bellais, was 17. He married Mrs. William de Bellais. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1180, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1150–1180":"1150–1180","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1180–1210":"1180–1210","1130–1155":"1130–1155","1133–1155":"1133–1155","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1210":"1210","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1150–1180":"11